What are Lists

  • list is a sequence of values.
    • Real life examples of lists:
    • shopping list, mobile phone contact list, recipe ingredients list
  • create a list in Python; the simplest is to enclose the elements in square brackets [ and ]
    • 3, 4] a list of numbers
    • [‘Tam’, ‘Liz’, ‘Jack’, ‘Omar’] a list of names
  • The values in lists are called elements or sometimes items.
  • The elements of a list don’t have to be the same type;
    • [‘John', 2.0, 5, [10, 20]] is also a list

Lists and Strings

Like a string, a list is a sequence of values. In a string, the values are characters; in a list, they can be any type.

Below is an example of a String.

greeting =‘Hello There!’

This is an example of a List:

greeting =[‘Hello’, ‘There!’]

5

Lists can be assigned to variables just like we do with Strings

Lists and Strings – Accessing list elements

    • The syntax for accessing the elements of a list is the same as for accessing the characters of a string—the bracket operator.
    • The expression inside the brackets speciﬁes the index.
    • The index starts at 0.

Lists are mutable

Unlike strings, lists can be changed (mutable). New elements can be added, deleted or a list can be sorted.

New items can be added to a list using append() method

    • The new element get added to the end of the list

Topic 5 - Lists and Dictionaries

11

VIT1102 - Introduction to Programming

Lists are mutable cont.…

Elements in a list can be deleted

    • Items of a list can be deleted using the pop() function.
    • the position is not provided the last item get removed.
    • index is provided an item in a given position can be removed.

VIT1102 - Introduction to Programming

Tuples

    • Tuples are collection of Strings and looks similar to Lists.

Example:

Pets =(‘dog’, ‘cat’, ‘fish’, ‘birds’)

    • Unlike lists, tuples are immutable.
    • Structure of a tuple can not be changed
    • Tuples are used when there is a need of an unchanging list.
    • list can be converted to a tuple.

Dictionaries

Topic 5 - Lists and Dictionaries

28

Key

Value

  • This is another important data structure present in Python.
  • Python dictionaries organize data by association as key/value pairs.
  • Each key:value pair is an element

Examples

Contacts in a phonebook as name : number

phonebook = {‘Jane’:’0422244576’, ‘Tom’:’0456755112’, ‘Lim’:’0345785116’}

Student marks information

marks = {‘name’: ‘Sophie Dodd’, ‘ID’: 4334550, ‘VIT1101’: 82, ‘VIT1102’: 100, ‘VIT1103’: 65,‘VIT1104’:72}

All the elements are enclosed in { }.

Key and Value are separated by a colon ‘:’

Each key:value pair is separated by a comma ‘,’.

VIT1102 - Introduction to Programming

Dictionaries contd..

    • Dictionaries are sorted after Python 3.4.
    • lists, sequence is maintained by number based indexing. In dictionaries, keys can be of any data type.
    • Keys are unique in each dictionary.
    • Keys must be of an immutable data type such as strings, numbers, or tuples.

Deleting an element in a dictionary

Deleting an element in a dictionary is carried out using the ‘pop’ command.

If key exists in dictionary then pop command removes the element with given key from dictionary and return its value.

Topic 5 - Lists and Dictionaries

35

VIT1102 - Introduction to Programming

Deleting cont.

If the deleting element is not present in the dictionary, pop command throw a keyError.

This can be avoided by using a default value ‘None’.
